solution:
First, we perform the operation in parentheses: \[6+5-4\times 3\div (2+1) = 6+5-4\times 3\div 3.\] Then, we perform multiplication and division, going from left to right: \begin{align*}
6+5-4\times 3\div 3 &= 6+5-12 \div 3 \\
&=6+5-4.
\end{align*} Finally, we perform addition and subtraction, going from left to right, to get our answer: \begin{align*}
6+5-4 &= 11-4 \\
&=\boxed{7}.
\end{align*}

We have \[
\begin{array}{@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c}
& & & 1 & \\
& 3 & 1 & 3. & 9 \\
+ & & 1 & 2. & 6
\\ \cline{1-5}
& 3 & 2 & 6. & 5 \\
\end{array}
\]Since $9+6=15$ in the right-most column is greater than 9, we record the 5 and "carry" the 10 to the next column as a 1 (shown over the second 3 in the addend 313.9). The answer is $\boxed{326.5}$.

